TY  - JOUR
T1  - Fatigued and Dissatisfied or Fatigued but Satisfied? Goal Orientations and Responses to High Job Demands
AU  - Van Yperen, Nico W.
AU  - Janssen, Onne
Y1  - 2002/12/01
PY  - 2002
DA  - 2002/12/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/3069431
DO  - 10.5465/3069431
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 1161
EP  - 1171
VL  - 45
IS  - 6
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - The present study tested dispositional goal orientation as an explanation for variation in responses to high job demands. Survey data from 322 university employees demonstrated that Job demands were positively related to fatigue, for all combinations of goal orientation. In line with our main proposition, only when an individual's performance orientation was stronger and his or her mastery orientation was weaker, were higher perceived Job demands accompanied by a decline in job satisfaction. The managerial implications of these findings are discussed.
AB  - The present study tested dispositional goal orientation as an explanation for variation in responses to high job demands. Survey data from 322 university employees demonstrated that Job demands were positively related to fatigue, for all combinations of goal orientation. In line with our main proposition, only when an individual's performance orientation was stronger and his or her mastery orientation was weaker, were higher perceived Job demands accompanied by a decline in job satisfaction. The managerial implications of these findings are discussed.
